column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility for unloading and consolidation into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility. Louisiana State Police were notified and assigned incident number 12-01247.

column168: During a routine load check, a driver hauling a van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste to the intended disposal site, noticed a small leak coming from his trailer.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The leak was determined to be coming from the nose of the trailer.  After unloading the entire trailer, the leak was determined to be coming from this shipment and also another one on the same trailer.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the absorbent material used to clean up the spill and a shovelful of dirt that had been picked up from the ground.
column169: The drum showed visible signs of aging and should have been inspected both by the generator and the driver before loading and accepting.  The drum was not leaking at the time of pick up nor during storage and loading at the intermediate truck transfer facility but was unable to withstand the rigors of transportation.

A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  When doing his routine post trip inspection, the driver noticed that one of the flexbins had split down the side, leaking the sludge-like material all over the trailer floor.  No material left the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and repacked the material into a suitable salvage container.  It was determined that the entire shipment should be overpacked as the flexbins all showed signs that the contents may spill.  The shipment was then transferred to a trailer being loaded for the intended waste disposal facility.  The Illinois Emergency Management Agency was notified, incident number H20120190.  As an RQ spilled out, the NRC was notified, incident number 1005223.
column169: The customer had been previously warned that there was too much moisture content in these flexbins, after a spill three weeks ago.  The profile has been suspended pending the customer making changes in their process.

column168: The fork-lift operator accidentally cracked the wall of one of the fibre drums containing Environmentally hazardous substance, solid, n.o.s. with the tip of an airline pallet that he was moving from one area of the warehouse to another.  The location of the damage was about 1 quarter from the top of the entire height of the drum. The crack to the wall of the drum was approximately 10 inches in length and the amount of the hazardous material released was approximately one tablespoon.  The release time was approximately 1 second.  At the time of discovery the damage to the drum was temporarily covered with tape and placed inside a plastic salvage container.  The package will be re-packed by a qualified D.G. packer and documentation will be revised.  The small spill was cleaned up as per ERG drill code 9L, with clean shovel into clean dry container and covered, then it was moved away from spill area.
column169: The fork-lift operator will be re-trained in standard fork-lift safety operations.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  The forklift operator picked up the drum with the beak type drum grabber and punctured the side of the drum.  When he set it down a small amount of material leaked out onto the concrete dock floor.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spill.  The leaking drum was placed into a suitable salvage container along with the cleanup material.  The shipment was then loaded into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  The Louisiana State Police were notified--incident number 12-01384.
column169: The forklift operator was cautioned to slow down and use more care when using the drum grabber attachment.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into trailers destined for various intended waste disposal facilities.  A drum was found to have leaked a small amount from the bung on top of and down the side of the drum.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the spilled material was cleaned up with an absorbent material and the bung closure on the drum was found to be missing the gasket.  A new closure was installed, the absorbent material was placed into the drum and the shipment was loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  The Louisiana State Police were notified--incident number 12-01386.
column169: The shipper was notified of the incident and that they shipped the drum without a proper closure in place.

column168: CCBX 2430, moving under FRA OTMA 12030229 due to a previously reported package exception, was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in the area of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives and React Environmental responded and discover product vapor was escaping from the gasket area between the tank nozzle and the mounting flange.  Attempts to stop the release by tightening the flange bolts were unsuccessful.    The contents of the car was transferred to trucks for further handling and delivery.  The car will move as a residue shipment under FRA OTMA-3 guidelines to Rescar in Dubois, PA, for cleaning, inspection and repair.    NOTE: THIS FOLLOW-UP/SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED TO CORRECT ERRORS INVOLVING THE OTMA REFERENCES IN THE ORIGINAL REPORT NARRATIVE. THE ORIGINAL REPORT HAD THE OTMA-3 AND OTMA 12030229 REFERENCES NOTED ABOVE IN REVERSE ORDER. THE MOVE COVERED BY THIS REPORT WAS UNDER THE AUTHORITY OF FRA OTMA-3 GUIDELINES. THE ABOVE NARRATIVE IS ACCURATE.

SHLX 100 was  noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, WEL Environmental, responded and found product vapor was originating from the bottom outlet due to a defective bottom outlet cap gasket.  All sealing surfaces and threads were cleaned, the gasket replaced and the cap properly applied and tightened stopping the release.    At the time of the response to the above car two other molten sulfur cars from the same shipper were noted releasing product vapor.      GATX 208865 was inspected and was found to have the bottom outlet valve cap gasket missing.   All sealing surfaces and threads were cleaned, a new gasket was installed and the cap properly applied and tightened stopping the release.    TILX 150734 was inspected and the bottom outlet cap gasket was found with dried material between the gasket and sealing surfaces which had prevented the gasket from properly seating.  All sealing surfaces and threads were cleaned, the gasket replaced and the cap properly applied and tightened stopping the release.

column168: On 03/03/2012 at 1149 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Pascagoula Mississippi yard discovered PPNX 1016, a residue tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking. The car was isolated and the  loader, Mississippi Phosphates, NRC and Mississippi DEQ were notified, CHEMTREC Report # 2012-03-03-00088. United States Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line valve plug not installed and the liquid line valve slightly open. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Mississippi Phosphate representatives. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. No 7.1 is required.     Note: Transammonia is the shipper of record although Mississippi Phosphate unloaded the car and released the residue tank in this non compliant condition.     Cause Code: 119  NARRI: 5(4+9+2) X (2+0) = 150

On March 6, 2012 at 1737 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Cumberland yard were informed by onsite Federal Railroad Inspectors (FRA), that AMOX 13373, a loaded tank car of molten sulfur had three (3) out of the six (6) securement bolts less than tool tight and had a small amount of product atop of the tank car. The tank car was isolated, the shipper, local, state and federal agencies as applicable were notified, CHEMTREC report #2012-0306-00225.  SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found three (3) out of the six (6) manway securement bolts less than tool tight and approximately 0.5 gallons of hardened product on the exterior of the tank car. Contractor personnel properly secured the manway securement bolts, removed the excess product from the exterior of the tank car, and then it was released for transport.    Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 ( 5 + 1 + 0 ) x ( 2+ 0 ) = 60     This incident did require a special switching move.    A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report is not required for this incident.

This shipment (1743-2892) was received in LAX inbound from STL. The shipment was described as Biological Substance Category B on the original airway bill. Also, screened under alternate screening for exempt biological substance category B. The condition of the box was wet with a yellow hue to the leaking fluid. The box was not crushed, torn or broken open, but there was one corner of the box that had a hole, which we assumed to be the source of the leakage. There was leaked fluid all over the cart. Material was cleaned up internally and with disinfectant. Customer was called and confirmed that the box contained dry ice and urine. Box was not opened to verify, but it seems that the inner packaging did not contain the required absorbent material or secondary packaging.
THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT PROPERLY HANDLED DURING SORT OPERATIONS AND BROKE OPEN, RELEASING CONTENTS FROM TWO INNER PACKAGES WHICH DESTROYED THE SHIPPING LABEL AND PACKAGE MARKS OF THE OUTER PACKAGE.
column169: PROPER HANDLING OF PACKAGE WOULD HAVE LIKELY PREVENTED THIS LEAKAGE. PROPER PACKAGE HANDLING WOULD LIKELY HAVE PREVENTED THIS DAMAGE AND RELEASE OF MATERIAL.

column168: On March 6, 2012 at 1715 hrs., personnel at Milepost MP CJ 44.5 on the Northern Subdivision on an Interchange track discovered MWCX 460072, a loaded covered hopper car of ammonium nitrate, leaking from the bottom of the car. On 3/13/2012 at approximately 0915 am, container SMLU 255447 was discovered leaking.  The unit was placed in a leaking container mitigation pad.  The shipper then contracted a hazardous materials response company (SWS Environmental) to mitigate the spill.  A leaking drum was discovered leaking.  A pallet cut the drum due to the fact that drums were packed too tight. Approximately one gallon leaked out.  The leaking drum was placed in an overpack drum and the spillage in the container was cleaned.  All cleanup materials were properly disposed.
column169: The drums should not have been packed tight.  This would have prevented this incident.  There was more than enough room in this unit to have packed them correctly.

column168: When the daylight yard job of Rook Yard went to work Centtenial Energy, the conductor noticed that tank car UTLX 953074 had a pipe sticking out from the side of the protective houseing which was leaking a liquid. He notified the Wheeling and Lake Erie Dipsatcher who then in turn notified the Wheeling Environmental Officer.  During the notifications, the Transloader of the Centennial cars arrived on scene to mitigate the situation.  It was found the the Snappy Joe deviced used to load the car was left installed on the car when the loading crew left and had failed at some point causing liquid to run out.
column169: It is recommened that proper securement of the rail car be done when the rail cars are no longer going to be attended.

UPON A CLEAR WALKPATH DRUM INITIALLY CONTAINING THE LIQUID WAS RETRIEVED FROM INSIDE OF TRAILER, FOUND EMPTY WITH A LARGE CRACK ACROSS THE BOTTOM INDICATING HAVING BEEN DROPPED.  MATERIALS INCLUDING CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD FROM BOXES INSIDE OF THE TRAILER, ABSORBENT AND SODIUM BICARB EMPLOYED TO CLEANUP, AS WELL AS DESIGNATED PPE WERE PUT THROUGH THE DMP PROCESS UPON RETURN TO PSC.

column168: As the driver pulled into the consignee's driveway, a woman in a Ford Explorer pulled in behind him and said that when he accelerated away from a traffic light a mist came of the trailer.  Her windows were open and now she said that her face had a slight burning sensation.  The Police and Fire Department responded to the incident.  The woman was given first aid treatment at the scene and then transported to the hospital as a precaution.  At the hospital she was given additional treatment and released.  An investigation at the scene revealed that the ball valve on the presure relief valve was slightly open.  The consignee brought out soda ash to neutralize the material that had spilled to the ground.  The Fire Department swept it up and the consignee put it in to their treatment system.  After the tank was unloaded the consignee decontaminated and washed the tank exterior.

column168: An inbound BNSF train was reported with an unspecified leaking tank car. Local BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were summoned to inspect this arriving train on the main track. Responders reported finding entrained tank car DBUX 301815 with fresh product stains on its side shell. A detailed inspection under the closed, pinned and sealed (intact seal Savage 0001677) valve housing cover on DBUX 301815 revealed the leak source at the base of the liquid valve. This threaded liquid valve was loose on its threaded connection at least one full turn. The liquid valve was tool tightened which ended any further product release. The valve housing cover was then closed and pinned.  Spillage atop DBUX 301815 was evaporating and very little ground impact was observed.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Date: 03/03/2012 // 8:24 PM EST // A/C: N412MC a B747F  Route: From. Guam A.F.Base (PGUA) to Misawa A.F.Base, (RJSM)     The flight crew phone patched the company's operations center reporting a spill,  apparent residual fuel, in an ULD containing an exposed F16 replacement tank.  The in-flight mechanic contained an approximate 0.25L of the substance and once in the ground he proceeded to clean / decontaminate the pallet and surrounding area accordingly. Adjacent ULDs, aircraft floor, roller tracks and power drive units were also checked for possible contamination and cleaned respectively. The aircraft was then release by him to continue in service.  The aircraft was not declared under emergency at any time during this event.  NRC and FAA were also notified on situation as early as practicable.  It has been determined that the residual fuel may have been leaked through an unsecured cap on the “presumed empty” tank when exposed to conditions normally encountered in air transport. Also note that it was reported the tanks were exposed to heavy rain sometime before the flight; however, we could not verify is inclement weather could have be a contributing factor for this event.
column169: The USAF base staff, through its applicable Air Terminal Manager, GS -12 Charles Kucharski, was notified on the event.   We have been advised that during the joint inspection process the inspector asked the unit for tank transport status,  i.e. if there was fuel in the PODS, and it was  stated the PODS were empty. Unfortunately the joint inspector may have failed to verify if fuels were in the tank and consequently the DD Form 2133 joint inspection form was not accurately completed.   The unit has been briefed to ensure the process is clearly adhered to and that any applicable check is confirmed before all blocks, that are applicable on the DD Form 2133, are properly completed.     The company has also briefed our direct staff member at base to ensure the USAF process is followed and to visually double check all replacement tanks despite being offered as empty / purged.     We are confident that this has been and unintentional overlook and that there was no intention to offer such a tank with a residual. Despite this believe, the USAF decertified the joint inspector who performed the joint inspection in question. USAF also notified the re-deploying unit and they are taken appropriate actions on their personnel as well.

column168: Today courier picked up 2 packages from a FedEx Ship Center and he believed they contained dry ice.  The courier and ship center contacted the shipper via the telephone number provided on the airbill, and asked the shipper if either shipment contained dry ice.  The shipper notified them that they did not and only contained gel packs as well as wet ice cubes.  We took them to the DG Area and opened both packages to examine the contents.  Both packages contained food and sufficient amounts of dry ice.  The two package tracking numbers are: AWB# 8001-0709-4194 and AWB# 8001-0709-4183.  I contacted FAA Michael Givens and advised him of the situation 11:15CST.  I also am forwarding Mr. Givens pictures of the inside of the packages.

column168: At approximately 3:30am on March 15th, we had an over fill of diesel fuel at the Sparta Fuel 24. I arrived on scene around 4:15am and assessed the situation. The Sparta Fire Department provided first response and had contained the spilled fuel prior to its entry into a nearby storm sewer. Absorbent materials were brought to the site and applied to the affected area (approximately 10ft x 150ft). The material was cleaned up later that morning and disposed of in a solid waste dumpster. The release was reported to the appropriate national and state agencies and follow up reporting has been completed. Calculations on the fuel ordered versus what was delivered compared that to the inventory readings on the fueling system and the estimated amount is between 50 & 150 gallons.

Tractor and trailer were traveling West in the center lane of IH-10 in Beaumont, TX.  Tractor and trailer had just come out of a curve in the interstate and wre driving on a slight grade when driver felt vehicle lean to right, as if a tire had low pressure.  Vehicle continued to lean right until both tractor and trailer rolled onto the right side of the vehicle.  vehicle slid on right side until coming to a stop blocking all 3 westbound lanes.  Driver stated he wass going maybe, 50 to 55 mph.  Speed limit on road is 65.  This was 1410 CST.  All West bound lanes were closed and East bound IH-10 lanes were closed until 2330 CST when IH-10 East bound lanes were opened.  There was a small discharge of about 20 gallons of liquid.  Police, fire, and EMS response was within a few minutes.  Traffic both directions ware rerouted and area secure.  Absolute Transportation Environmental Co. cleaned up and contained spill area.  Tow units uprighted tractor and trailer.  Load was checked for any further leakeage by environmental crew, none found.  East bound lanes of freeway reopened at this time, 2330 CST.  Load was quantity of 6o, 55 gallon drums.  Entire load shifted in container.  All barrels were offloaded using fork lift.  Barrels were inspected for damage.  3 barrels were damaged and placed in overpack drums.  Entire load was transferred to new tractor trailer.  Damaged Equipment was removed from scene and area cleaned up.  All west bound lanes opened 1000 CST.
column169: Emphasize to all drivers through ongoing training the risk of rollover accidents.  Witness to accident stated stron winds appeared to blow trailer over.  Emphasize the power of cross winds in driver safety meeetings.  Officer on scene stated a lot of accidents in this area, they are about to begin rebuilding IH-10 bridge just East of this accident.  This should make this entire area of IH-10 safer.  There is a grade coming off bridge and into area where driver accident occured.  Warning signs for high crosswinds could be placed in hazardous areas such as this portion of IH-10.

column168: A driver picked up a load on a rented vacuum box.  He performed his pre-trip inspection and everything was normal.  After driving a short distance on the highway, while stopped at a red light, he noticed that the front inlet/outlet cap was missing and liquid was spilling out.  He moved the truck to the side of the road, called police and set up a barricade over the approximately 5 gallons of liquid that had spilled onto the road.  The police and fire department arrived and properly closed the lane.  A response crew was notified and upon arrival, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the pavement and material that had spilled onto the vacuum box and truck.  The rental company arrived with a replacement pvc outlet cap to replace the broken one.  The load then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  Illinois Emergency Management Agency was notified--incident number H2012-0230
column169: The pvc outlet cap was intact when the load was picked up.  The cap was defective and blew out as soon as the vehicle was on the highway.  The rental company replaced the cap and the unit was placed back in service.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported tank car DBUX 302021 with residue product around the threaded connection of the closed bottom operated bottom outlet valve's (BOV) closure cap (BOC). The BOV's operating handle was in the closed position and pinned.  DBUX 302021 was isolated in the railyard. A response contractor was summoned and inspected DBUX 302021 on 3/19/2012. Responder reported that the BOC was easily turned with a 36 inch pipe wrench. No active product residue release was observed, but a wet product ring was noted at the BOC threaded connection.  Internal pressure of 3 psi was bled off via the vapor valve. All valves and other fittings were found secure. Little to no product heel inside the tank was observed during inspection via the opened manway.  A containment receptacle was placed under the BOV and the BOC was removed. The BOC gasket appeared serviceable. The BOC was reapplied and the BOV was worked open and closed via the operating handle and it functioned as intended. After the BOV was closed, the BOC was again removed and drained of captured residue product. The BOC was then reapplied and tool tightened. Response was concluded by 1530 hrs. MDT, 3/19/2012  Intact seal PAA Richmond 11419 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal TIS 5939; intact manway seal MAPW 15797 replaced by seal TIS 5938 and intact BOV seal PAA Richmond 11420 replaced by seal TIS 5940.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A tanker was loaded and it was noticed that the tank test had expired.  The load was being transferred to another tanker in containment when the cam lock failed.  The driver shut down the operation and placed a bucket under the valve along with an absorbent material on the spilled material.  A response crew was notified who donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the affected area.  The load was transferred after the valve was temporarily repaired and the load was delivered without further incident.  The trailer was taken out of service for valve repair and tank test.  Texas CEQ was notified, incident number 20120953
column169: The driver was issued a warning letter for loading the vehicle with an expired tank test.  The location responsible for the trailer was also talked to about having a mechanism in place to track expiration dates of tank tests.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On 1 March 2012 at 1045 hrs., personnel on the CSXT mainline at MP ANB693, discovered intermodal trailer NONZ 53574, on flatcar TTEX 353622, a loaded trailer of batteries, leaking from a large crack in trailer just in front of wheels. The flatcar was isolated and the shipper, Romar Transportation Systems (AMANDA GORMAN 773-650-1642), GA DNR (OPR 136-no report) and NRC (Mr. Taliaferro) were notified (NRC #1004472). First Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found acid leaking from a large hole in trailer onto flatcar. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel neutralized the spilled acid and transferred the lading into UMXU 236437 for delivery to the Jacksonville Intermodal terminal via highway then loaded onto another train to destination.

On 3/09/12 at 1043 hrs., FRA personnel in the CSXT Hawthorne yard discovered UTLX 23329, a loaded  tank car of Toxic Liquid, Corrosive NOS, venting from the vacuum relief valve flange and blind flange area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Heritage Crystal Clean was notified and CHEMTREC report #2012-03-09-00062. Summit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 2 of 4 flange bolts on the vacuum relief valve and 4 of 4 blind flange bolts were less than tool tight. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured all bolts and nuts. The leak was stopped and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 442  NARRI: 5(5+5+1)x(2+0)= 110

On March 14, 2012 at 1620 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Buffalo Frontier yard discovered UTLX 208110, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S. leaking product from the top of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, RPMG, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report #20120314-00283. NYS-DEC and the City of Buffalo Emergency response agencies were also notified. A CSXT HMS Manager found a release of product from the connection between the base of the liquid line valve, and the welded pipe nipple of the valve assembly mounting plate. The liquid line valve body was tightened  of a turn and the release was stopped.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper Representative.     This incident will require an AAR 7.1 report.    Cause Code: 282   NARRI:  2 (5+3+0)x(2+0) = 32

column169: We have not noticed any trend with the dome lid on the rubber-lined trailers leaking.  the linings are checked as required and this one was just not tighened down enough.

CALLED TO RED SECONDARY AT 21:42 FOR A LEAKING HAZ-MAT. FRED MERZA FOUND THE PACKAGE. NICK BANEVICIUS RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. THE PACKAGE CONSISTED OF GLASS BOTTLES DIVIDED WITH PACKAGING MATERIAL AND DOUBLED BOXED. THE BOTTLES SEEMED TO HAVE HAD A LOOSE CAP AND LEAKED OUT. THE OUTER BOX WAS IN GOOD CONDITION (NOT CRUSHED OR DAMAGED).  FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO DMP AREA
PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED AND WAS NOTICED THAT IT WAS LEAKING. AT THAT POINT SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED.

PACKAGE WAS SORTED ONTO THE BELT. WHEN PACKAGE ARRIVED AT THE DESTINATION BELT IT WAS OBSERVERED TO BE LEAKING. RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED IN THE APPROPRIATE MANNER TO THE LEAKING PACKAGE. PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND WAS RETURNED TO THE DMP AREA FOR APPROPRIATE ACTION. RESPONDER CHECKED TO MAKE SURE NO ONE WAS EXPOSED OR INJURED BY THE LEAKING MATERIAL. CORRECT PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED TO DECONTAMINATE THE BELT AND ANY OTHER EFFECTED AREA. WHEN OPENING PACKAGE RESOPNDER NOTICED THAT ONE OF THE CAPS ON ONE OF THE BOTTLES WAS BENT FROM AN IMPACT CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK.
column169: PACKAGE AND ACCOMPANYING PRODUCT WERE PACKED CORRECTLY. ADDITIONAL PACKING MATERIAL COULD HAVE PREVENTED ACCIDENT. MOVING PACKAGE ON IRREG TRAIN INSTEAD OF SORTING BY BELT COULD HAVE ALSO HELPED TO PREVENT THE ACCIDENT.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A SPILL IN UNLOAD 2 DOOR 22. I FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. I WORE THE PROPER PPE I CONTAINED, SOLIDIFIED AND PROCESSED THE MATERIAL FOLLOWING THE UPS DISPOSALS PROCEDURES. I PLACED THE MATERIAL INTO A BAG.

PACKAGE CAME DOWN THE SLIDE AT THE PACKAGE CAR. STEVE CORRUTHERS WAS IN THE AREA AND SAW THAT IT WAS WET AT THE CORNER OF THE BOX. HE CLEARED THE AREA AND CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. SERENA BIETZ RESPONDED TO THIS PACKAGE IN FULL PPE GOGGLES, GLOVES, BOOTS AND APRON. FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET. DID A PH TEST ON THE WET AREA TO MAKE SURE IT WAS COMING FROM THE PACKAGE. WHEN IT WAS DETERMINED THE WET AREA WAS INDEED LIQUID FROM THE PACKAGE, FOLLOWED THE DT AND RS TO CONTAIN THE PACKGE AND READY IT FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO THE DMP. THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED IN THE DMP WITH FULL PPE ON. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A LOOSE CAP ON ONE OF THE BOTTLES WAS THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.

PRELOADER REMOVED PACKAGE FROM CONVEYOR USING THE PROPER LIFTING METHODS.  PRELOADER GRABBED THE PACKAGE AT OPPOSITE  CORNERS AND HIS HAND FELT A WET SUBSTANCE.  PRELOADER IMMEDIATELY WASHED HIS HANDS.

WHEN I WENT TO PICK UP THE BOX OFF OF THE BELT I DISCOVERED THE SIDE WAS OPEN AND THEN CAREFULLY MOVED THE BOX SO IT WOULD NOT FALL APART.  I OBSERVED A WET CORNER ON THE BOX.  I SHUT THE BELT OFF AND PROCEEDED TO ISOLATE THE BOX AND REMOVE IT AS PER THE CURRENT PROCEDURE FOR DAMAGED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN I OPENED THE PACKAGE I FIRST CHECKED TO SEE IF THE CAPS WERE LOOSE AND ONE WAS LOOSE.
column169: THE MANUFACTURER NEEDS TO MAKE SURE THAT THE CAPS ARE TIGHT IN THE QA DEPARTMENT.  PERHAPS THE BOTTLES' TOPS COULD BE SECURED WITH TAPE.  THIS COULD PREVENT THE VIBRATIONS THROUGH TRANSIT FROM LOOSENING THE CAP FURTHER.

column168: CALLED TO SPILL AT BAY 474, SUPERVISOR FOUND PACKAGE, HAD A SMELL, NO VISIBLE DAMAGE.  INNER PACKAGE WAS GLASS BOTTLE WITH LOOSE PLASTIC CAP.  CORRUGATED WITH FIBERBOARD.
LEAKING PACKAGE WAS REPORTED. THE RESPONDER ARRIVED AND USED THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND THEN PROCESSED THE PACKAGE AND CONTENTS THROUGH THE DMP.
column169: FISHER SCIENTIFIC NEEDS TO CHEcK ALL BOTTLES BEFORE SHIPPING OUT.

While unloading a shipment of drums at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a drum slipped out of the drum grabber and tipped over on the dock surface.  The drum was uprighted and a response crew was summoned.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum and the small amount of liquid that had seeped from the material and come out of the drum was cleaned up with a suitable absorband material.  The shipment was then loaded on a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: A new employee was training and loading the shipment.  The forklift was travelling too fast and the drum slipped out of the drum grabber.  The employee is receiving additional training.

column168: A van trailer was loaded in the intermediate truck storage yard destined for the intended waste disposal site.  During a routine yard check, a small amount of material was found to be leaking.  The van was placed into the dock and a response crew was notified.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, they unloaded the trailer and found a drum with a small leak on the bottom weld.  The liquid that leaked out from the solid material had separated from the material.  A suitable absorbent was applied and the drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum.  The cleanup materials were also placed into the salvage drum and the trailer was reloaded without further incident.
column169: The drum was not leaking when picked up nor when inspected and loaded by the truck transfer personnel.  The customer was notified of the incident and defective drum and was going to more closely inspect drums prior to loading.

column168: During the routine check in process at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, a small leak was notice in the dome lid area.  A small amount dripped down from the drain line onto the concrete.  The rental tanker was taken to the containment area of the sample rack and it was discovered that a wing nut on the dome was loose and it was also believed that the dome lid gasket had failed.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material from the concrete, side of the tanker and inside the dome area.  The tanker then proceeded into the intended waste disposal facility where it was unloaded.
column169: The tanker was returned to the rental company to be taken out of service and repaired.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was paked in containment at Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in Bristol CT for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. While transferring one container a drum was punctured by an exposed nail on a pallet causing the release of waste.Response personnel cleaned up spillage donning the proper PPE and placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. All required local fire dept and state DEP reports were made.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed by the driver. The drum was punctured due to a defective pallet used for reloading the drums for continued transportation. In order to prevent a recurrence, plant personell met for a safety meeting immediatly after the spill was cleaned up regarding the importance of inspecting future pallets for defects to prevent future incidents of this type from reoccuring.

THE DRIVER FELT THERE WAS NO SAFE LOCATION TO PULL OVER SO DRIVER PROCEEDED TO OUR FACILITY AT 858 DISTRIBUTION DRIVE, APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE AWAY. At 04:21 p.m. on March 6, 2012, it was discovered that car GATX 80226 was leaking from the top of the car.  Car is loaded with hexane.  Car was on south end of long 6 track in Shreveport, LA.  No injuries were reported.  All concerned have been notified.    Carl Akins, KCS, was already at the Shreveport Yard so he began to do an initial research and PPE selection for response to the Hexane commodity. Mr. Akins also called response partner,to inform him of situation. Mr. Akins arrived on the scene at 4:45 p.m. and Mike arrived five minutes later. The Shreveport Terminal Director assisted KCS with getting the appropriate tracks locked out.    It was observed that a steady trickle of liquid coming from the car at a rate of about 20 ounces per minute coming from the protective housing. After opening the protective housing KCS found the flange on the liquid line to be improperly secured. Two of the bolts were less than hand tight. After wrench tightening the bolts, the leak was mitigated. The leak was stopped at approximately 5:15 p.m. LA State Police Officer Jay Hardy arrived on the scene at approximately 5:20 p.m. He climbed onto the car and was briefed on the leak situation and the  mitigation. The protective housing was closed and a new security seal was installed.    The car was released at 5:45 p.m.    File Note: Item 19 - the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27 - Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Local train crew had reported product leaking from top of tank car.  Immediate response to the area failed to locate leaking tank car.  Car was thought to have been interchanged with BNSF Railroad.  On 3-19-12, car was located in Yard 5, track 25, and was not leaking.  Inspection of car revealed that product had vented from the pressure relief valve due to car being shell full at the time due to product expansion from radiant sun heat.  Pressure check of car revealed internal car pressure at 5 psi. Top and sides of car were cleaned and affected area below car were remediated by  environmental contractor.  On 3-20-12 car was delivered and off loaded without further incident. **Supplemental Descriptions  - Local train crew reported product leaking from top of car.  Upon inspection, product was no longer leaking from car, however there were signs that product had leaked from the pressure relief valve.  Further investigation revealed that car leaked due to excessive pressure build up from within the car. Car was vented, and arrangements were made to have car cleaned and area remediated.  Car was released to continue onto destination without further incident.

column62: Threads Worn or Cross Threaded; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Inbound terminating train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained tank car GATX 6326 leaking product from the top fitting area. BNSF responders depressurized GATX 6326 ending the product release at the liquid line's closure cap area. Inspection of the liquid line closure cap revealed it was approx. 1/4 turn passed hand tight. GATX 6326 deemed safe to move and it was isolated in the railyard for further inspection by shipper representatives to determine root cause of this release. Shipper representative inspected GATX 6326 and reported that the liquid eduction pipe threads were 'somewhat coarse', thus providing a pathway for product under pressure to escape from the threaded liquid eduction line's threaded connection at the closure cap.  The closure cap's gasket was in a serviceable condition. The closure cap was tool tightened to approx. 1 1/2 to 2 turns passed hand tight. Product spillage on the tank shell was neutralized with baking soda and no ground spillage was reported.
column169: The shipper is initiating measures to eliminate future like occurrences. These measures include changes to closure cap gasketing, depressurizing liquid eduction system during loading, testing for closure cap sealing integrity after loading using up to 25 psig air pressure and additional pre-trip inspection audit checks.

column168: UTLX 663227 was noted by carrier personnel with product sloshing from the top of the car during switching.  Car isolated and shipper notified.     Shipper representatives, SET Environmental, responded and found six of six manway cover bolts loose with one bolt not applied.  All manway securement bolts were properly secured and made tool tight stopping the release.

PPGX 3051 was noted by carrier personnel with product dripping from the bottom outlet valve.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and reseated the bottom outlet valve operating handle and tightened the valve cap stopping the release.

column168: This incident occurred due to human error.  The driver opened the caps up on the underground storage tanks to get stick readings and in the process did not get the proper readings.  The driver began to drop product in one tank and the cap was not placed back on the other tank. The product pushed up through the other tank and into the spill bucket and a small amout outside spill bucket.(5 gallons total)  The driver saw the product coming out of uncapped tank and capped it to stop the flow of product. Driver was able to clean up entire spill with the spill kit he had in the trailer.
column169: Driver was coached on the incident and delivery procedures were reviewed.

column42: ETHANOL AND GASOLINE MIXTURE OR ETHANOL AND MOTOR SPIRIT MIXTURE OR ETHANOL AND PETROL MIXTURE, WITH MORE THAN 10% ETHANOL
column168: SOCI Petroleum driver was unloading 87 Gasohol at the Northfield Sunoco station. There is two 10,000 gallon tanks that are manidfold. The driver was unloading into the first tank and the first tank was filling up and came close to be full and the pressure from the first tank caused the cap from the second tank to blow off and and gas started to flow out of the second tank and approximately 315 gallons spilled onto the ground.    The local Fire Department , The OHIO EPA, The National Responce Center was notified.  We also called out Inland Waters Enviormental Company for spill clean up.    The duration of the release was 7 hours. The gas traveled to a storm sewer and Inland Waters supplied a vac truck to flush the storm sewer and gather the gas. Site was monitored by the EPA And Inland Waters for two days.
column169: We held a safety meeting with the driver and reviewed the cause of the spill and also we have also sent out to all drivers a letter stating the issues that caused the spill and make sure every driver is aware of thecause of the spill and to let them the proper prcedure is when unloading into tanks that are manifold together.

column168: GATX 75631 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, WEL Environmental, responded and found a slow drip from the bottom outlet valve flange.  Attempts to tighten the bolts to stop the release were unsuccessful.  The contents of the car were transferred to another tank car for futher handling.  GATX 75631 will be forwarded to a tank car shop under FRA Movement Approval.      The carrier employee who discovered the release was transported to a local medical facility where he was treated with oxygen and released.

Truck was proceeding east on RT 724 with about 1100 gallons of Fuel Oil in storage tank, when a passenger veChile travelling west crossed the double yellow line and was aimed directly at front of truck. Driver of truck got over to allow as much room as possible using the berm and applied the brakes.The car continued its path and struck the truck on drivers side in front of the rear wheels, causing the left side of truck to leave the road surface. The momentum caused the truck to roll 3 times coming to rest on its wheels and with the tank still attached but resting 90 degrees to its normal mounting, over a drainage ditch. The integrity of the tank was not compromised, however the piping between truck and tank broke allowing fuel into drainage ditch, onto the already flowing small amount of water from field runoff. Fire company personel arrived within 5 minutes and put booms and pads in the ditch and on the top of water stopping the flow of oil within 50 feet of the origin. Pads and booms were removed, oil and water was removed by vacuum truck. Within 24 hours, contaminated soil was removed for disposal and new soil put in place.

column168: The unit was traveling on a two lane road at 50-55 mph. As the unit traveled over the crest of a hill, he observed 5 oncoming vehicles. The 5th vehicle, a pickup truck, began to pass the other 4 vehicles, all cars. Our unit began to brake, seeing the distance to short for the pickup to pass safely. The pickup made no attempt to slow down or return to it's lane. Our driver noticed noticed the pickup's windshield was frosted and the driver's ability to see was limited. Our driver then applied maximum braking and edged to the berm to avoid a head-on collision. The pickup moved slightly over towards the other vehicles it was passing.It hit our unit in the left front causing the collision. Our unit was slowed to 30-35 mph at the point of impact. Due to the sudden surge of the liquid and loss of the left steer tire, our unit rolled onto it's right side across the roadway. The pickup was totaled, but the driver uninjured. Our driver was injured, but exited the vehicle. He was able to give valuable information to first responders and police as product was leaking from the manhole area. The EMA on sight coordinator stated that the lid was secure, but it was leaking from the hinge area of the lid due to the structural damage of the tank. A backhoe was brought in to create small ponds to contain the product leaking onto the roadway and traveling into a wooded area as advised by our driver. The NRC, DEP, & PEMA were notified. The product was contained in these small ponds. It was covered with plastic to prevent being disturbed until it cooled and solidified. The product was left in place for 3 days as it posed no threat to the environment. It was then removed with a limited amount of soil. The area affected was restored to it's natural state. The property owner stated it looked better than before the spill. The duration of the release was approximately 5 1/2 hours. That was about 617 gallons per hour or 10.3 gallons per minute. The actions taken by all first responders and the recovery personnel throughout the duration of the incident, are to be commended. Communication was also a key factor. After the cleanup and restoration, soil samples were taken and sent for testing .
column169: Our company trains our drivers with the latest training materials provided by J.J. Keller, PERS, and various other sources. We utilize online training tools and hands on material. Compliance is a never ending process. The safety of our drivers and other motorists who we share public roadways with, is our is our main priority. To always expect the unexpected is most important, even when a driver is faced with an unavoidable head on collision by fault of another vehicle. Split decisions by drivers absolutely determine what the end result will be. Even with the extreme force of the rollover to the structure of the tank trailer, the shell, though severely damaged, remained in tact. The product leaked through the dome lid hinge area and a limited amount through the vent assembly, which has no way of being closed. Since this incident, I have contacted E.D. ETNYRE, the manufacturer, requesting they construct an emergency shut off valve which could be closed to prevent product loss through the vent assembly in the event of a rollover. This area is already protected by a rollover protection box. Their engineers have devised a way to install such a valve. We are currently having these valves installed on our new purchases, and will eventually make the same updates to our current fleet. This procedure will help prevent product from escaping through the vent system. Due to the temperature on average of 300 plus degrees, these tank trailers require constant ventilation to prevent damage from expansion and contraction. We hope to never have the need for this valve, but knowing that it is in place, can only be a positive result.

column168: The customer tendered a non hazardous bill of lading to the trucker and ocean carrier and stated that the cargo was non hazardous under the DOT hazmat regulations.  The invoice that they later presented for the move listed all of the products as UN3082 with all of the hazmat information including the "X" in the HM column of the shipping paper and the emergency response phone number.  A containers involved were booking TX2552550 -  CONTAINER HRZU431004-6 and booking TX2556642 - Container SEAU868387-0.  All the shipments were UN3082 with various technical names.  The total quantity for both containers was 16,487 lbs.  Our documentation clerk recognized the hazardous information and requested a dangerous goods declaration including the signed certification statement.  The customer insisted that the cargo was non hazardous.  I phoned the customer and explained the conflict that had to be clarified.  The customer spoke with me with their regulatory and safety personnel on a conference call the third and discovered that their computer system had not captered the data as hazardous.  They are now making adjustments to their computer system to ensure that this problem is resolved.
column169: The customer should have validated the package marking and labeling with the shipping papers to ensure that everything matched.

column168: THE DRIVER ROLLED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ONTO ITS SIDE.    WAITING FOR CHP REPORT FOR CLARITY AND DETERMINATION.    THE CARGO TANK DID NOT LEAK.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CAUSED BY CONTRA COSTA COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM DURING PRODUCT TRANSFER.

Driver connected delivery hose to customer tank from transport tank and started delivery.  He secured the camlock ears where the hose connected to the transport tank but the connection failed and the camlock ears vibrated open and the hose disconnected allowing diesel to spill.  Driver immedietely shut down flow of product and used spill kit materials to contain spilled product in a defined area.  The spill was contained and since the ground was frozen did not penetrate the soil more than 2 inches. All free standing product was soaked up with absorbants. A cleanup contactor was contacted and they scraped up contaminated surface materials and replaced with clean materials.  The contaminated soils were properly disposed of at a registered landfill in Hill County.
column169: Reviewed the hose securement procedures with driver with specific focus on securing camlock ears.  Made certain driver understood how to secure camlock ears and the neccessity for doing so.

column168: TILX 150737 was involved in a multicar derailment that resulted in a tear in the tank shell measuring approximately two feet by three feet (photo attached).      The contents of the car ignited during the derailment along with two other non-hazardous material cars.  The fire was allowed to burn until it could be safely extinguished by pouring sand around the opening in the car stopping the release.      Approximately 100-125 people from 56 residences within a one-half mile radius of the incident were evacuated until the morning of March 29.  There were no injuries reported.    The tank car was cleaned and will be scrapped on-site.  All spilled material that was not consumed by the fire was recovered and properly disposed of.

On March 14, 2012, a US Xpress/Total Transportation tractor trailer was backing up to a dock when 4 5-gallon plastic pales of UN1263 Paint fell out of the trailer and released onto the asphalt/concrete parking lot. Approximately 20 gallons of material was released as a result of this incident. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site to perform cleanup operations. All of the released paint was collected and containerized for transportation and disposal. No storm drains, waterways or soils were impacted as a result of this release.

On March 15, 2012, a 1350 pound tank of UN3163 Liquefied gas, n.o.s. (Pentefluoroathane, Difluromethane), Class 2.2 had a broken valve and was leaking gas into the air at the R&L Carriers terminal. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site to perform cleanup operations. The contractor transported the leaking tank outside and allowed the material to evacuate from the cylinder.

column168: A vapor cloud was observed coming from container TCNU 998258 located in the Union Pacific Dupo Rail Yard. The release involved Hydrofluoric Acid and was a result of improper blocking and bracing by the shipper.      The load was incorrectly  braced with "2x4" material while the loading requirements for HZ in containers requires "2X6" material.  The incorrect B+B material caused the tote move and to subsequently release the HZ material,
column169: Review blocking and bracing requirments for HM shipments.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Highway 287 northbound, driver stopped abruptly, which caused freight to shift inside trailer, and damage one (1) 300-gallon tote.  The Waxahachie Fire Department responded to assess the site.  CRS Environmental of Ennis, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, free liquid was detected on the asphalt beneath the trailer, and within the broken up asphalt and surface soils.  CRS Environmental offloaded the trailer, and one (1) 300-gallon tote was discovered damaged.  Approximately 150 gallons released to the ground surface, and approximately 50 gallons released to trailer floor.  Absorbent material was applied to contain the free liquid, which was recovered along with contaminated surface soils and broken-up asphalt.  The remaining product was solidified with absorbents, and tote was broken down.  Spent absorbents, soils, broken-up asphalt, and the broken down tote were placed into one (1) rolloff box, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There was no impact or threat to state waters.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Lynden Transport, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

Approximately 10 gallons of ammonia solution was released from a loose cap on a tote and impacted the trailer floor. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup. The cap was tightened and the released product was neutralized. Granular absorbents were then applied to the impacted area and the waste was collected and containerized for disposal.

On March 17, 2012, a 30 gallon plastic drum of UN3264 Corrosive Liquid, acidic, inorganic, n.o.s. (Nitric Acid and Phosphoric Acid) cracked at the bottom of the drum and released approximately 30 gallons of material onto the trailer floor and soil shoulder. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site to perform cleanup operations. The environmental contractor neutralized the released material and utilized absorbents to clean the affected trailer floor. The contractor also excavated the contaminated soil, which was containterized for transportation and disposal. The area was backfilled and restored back to original condition. The contractor also placed the damaged drum along with the remaining material in an overpack drum for continued transportation. The cargo was unloaded, cleaned and loaded back onto the trailer after the trailer floor was cleaned. No storm drains or waterways were impacted as a result of this release.

column168: On 3/29/2012, at approximately 12:35, SWS Environmental was contacted by Matt Borchert of Florida East Coast Railway. At this time, Matt requested response to a tank car containing a residual amount of Ethyl Alcohol,that was seeping a small amount of product from the bottom outlet. SWS responded with two personnel, and after participating in a safety briefing and confirming track protection, inspected the car further.    Upon inspection of the car (ACFX 200152), we did not observe any obvious damage or vandalism, that would impact the serviceability of the car. We did observe moisture around the top of the bottom outlet cap, but it did not appear that the rate at which the product seeped out, was greater than the rate that it volatized in the open air. SWS did not witness product impacting any surface other than the cap itself.    FEC advised us that their personnel did tighten the bottom outlet cap with a pipe wrench, and did snug the top operated bottom valve as well. SWS personnel deployed absorbent padding beneath the bottom outlet as a precautionary measure, and using a five gallon pail to capture material, removed the bottom outlet cap. Once removed, approximately six to eight ounces of product fell into the bucket. When the cap was removed, all residual moisture around the thread and valve quickly dried up. The cap did not have a gasket installed and it is not known to us (SWS)if that particular cap was designed to have a gasket, and if so, whether or not a gasket would have prevented the seepage. We were able to look up into the bottom outlet and did not see any damage or obstruction that would prevent the valve from operating properly.    The bottom outlet valve was replaced and tightened with a pipe wrench. We then transferred the product captured in the pail, back into the car via the man way. When opening the man way cover, we did release a fair amount of pressure. The inside of the car looked to be in good condition, free of any obvious damage or decay. The man way cover was then closed and secured, and made tool tight with a pipe wrench.    The bottom outlet was then re-inspected and found not to be releasing product. It could be speculated, that with the valve not snug, and pressure building in the car,that product and/or vapor was forced into the loose cap, resulting in the moisture that was discovered today. It could also be speculated that with the pressure vented, the valve snugged, and the cap tightened, that the risk of reoccurrence has been reduced and/or removed.    Matt, The FRA contacted us once we returned to the shop and asked some questions about what we observed and the services we provided. He requested a short summary as well. With your permission, we can forward the above narrative to him, if that makes it easier for you. column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: At 9:18 Mr. Yost spoke to Ms. Vicki, Health and Safety Officer, of Caterpillar Logistics.  She told Mr. Yost that upon arrival two batteries were identified as being tipped over in the back of the trailer.  Mr. Yost spoke to the driver (Mr. Melton)  and authorized him to move his tractor and directed him to use his spill kit containing kitty litter and baking powder to cover the drips in the parking lot so traffic would not drive through the acid and spread the contamination.    At 9:54 Mr. Yost contacted Mr. Melton and was informed that he had been required to park next to a drain and that he was running out of spill supplies.  Mr. Yost spoke to him and told him that dirt could be used to make a berm to prevent entry into the storm drain.  The driver was able to use a piece of flat metal to gather soil and make a berm.  Mr.Yost explained to Mr. Melton that the ETA of the response contractor would be a little over three hours.    At 12:15 Mr. Wright of Con-way Transportation  contacted Mr. Yost and informed him that he had spoken to his customer and that Mr. Yost was to leave the four batteries on the trailer after they and the trailer had been deconned.    At 13:37 the response contractor arrived on site and determined  the small acid release was container.  Since Caterpillar would not let them use their dock and fork lift the response contractor had to rent local equipment to upright the batteries and secure them to the sides of the trailer.  Each battery weighed an estimated 1600 pounds.    At 17:42 SWS staff were back on site and had placed the hoist into the trailer.    At 19:11 three of the batteries had been moved and secured in a clean area of the trailer.  Both of the batteries which had been laying on their side were not damaged.  Sulfuric acid had only been leaking from the top fill caps on the battery.  Both of these batteries were wrapped in plastic an secured to the side of the trailer with ratchet straps.    The small amount of neutralize acid, broken boards from the pallets, and soil were placed into one 55-gallon drum and taken off site for disposal.
column169: The load shift which caused the batteries to tip over was caused by a hard braking event to avoid an accident.  The batteries were packaged securely and during routine transportation  cirsumstances  would have been sufficient to secure the load.

column168: Around 3:00 pm on Thursday 3/29/2012 Stericycle driver was leaving lunch in New Braunsfels, TX. Driver was making a right hand turn onto the frontage road. After the turn, 20-25 yards in the right hand lane on the frontage road the rear trailer over turned into the left lane on the frontage road. The driver immediately stopped and assessed the situation and made the proper notifications. There was an estimated 1/2 gallon of liquid that leaked out of the trailer onto the pavement. Stericycle immediately cleaned up liquid on pavement. Wrecker service was notified to upright the trailer and caused an estimated one hour shut down of the frontage road. Local authorities did not allow Stericycle to open the trailer at the scene and the trailer was taken to the wrecker service yard. No damages to any other property was sustained.

On 03/13/2012 at 1400 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Jacksonville Bush yard, discovered TILX 197105, a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S., leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, POET Biorefining was notified, CHEMTREC report #2012-0313-00152. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line valve slightly open and the valve handle stem packing nut was loose. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel tightened the packing nut on the liquid line valve handle and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.     Cause Code: 296  NARRI:2(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 32

column168: On 23 March, 2012 at 0422 hrs., a call to CSXT PSCC from Coffee County, GA PD, discovered intermodal flatcar FEC 71965 with loaded 20' container, KHLU821033, containing 53 drums of Anhydrous Stannic Acid was leaking from doors of container in the form of vapors. The car was isolated and Hamburg-SUD was notified, CHEMTREC report #2012-03-23-00048.  First Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one drum had been puntcured by nails protruding from the wood floor of the container, resulting in liquid leaking out, creating both liquid release and vapors. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative. Contractor personnel placed the leaking drum in overpack to stop product from leaking. The remaining lading was unloaded, instected and transferred into another container for delivery to destination. This incident did not require a special switching move.

column168: -  A TANKER TRUCK AND TRAILER HAULING FUEL FOR CASCADE PETROLEUM TRANSPORTATION INC., PORTLAND, CRASHED WHILE HEADING EASTBOUND ON STATE HIGHWAY 58 ABOUT FIVE MILES WEST OF OAKRIDGE, NEAR MILEPOST 31.5, AT ABOUT 9 A.M. MONDAY, MARCH 12.  -  TRAILER SPILLED APPROX. 3,100 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND 2,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL INTO ROADSIDE DITCH. TRUCK CONTAINING 4,400 GALLONS OF GASOLINE DID NOT SPILL ANY OF ITS CONTENT. REMAINING FUEL SAFELY PUMPED OUT OF TRUCK.  -  DRIVER, HIRED BY CASCADE PETROLEUM AND BASED IN MEDFORD, RECEIVED MINOR INJURIES AND WAS CITED BY OREGON STATE POLICE FOR FAILURE TO DRIVE WITHIN A LANE.  -  OREGON DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT QUALITY IS LEADING CLEANUP EFFORTS ALONG WITH U.S. ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY. ALSO ON-SCENE ARE REPRESENTATIVE OF OREGON DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND U.S. FOREST SERVICE.  -  24 HOMES NEAR OAKRIDGE EVACUATED AS SAFETY PRECAUTION ON MONDAY 3/12; RESIDENTS RETURNED TO HOMES LATER THAT EVENING.
column169: WE BELIEVE THAT THIS ROLL OVER WAS HUMAN ERROR, THAT THE DRIVER MOMENTARILY DOZED OFF AND WOKE WITH A JERK OF THE WHEEL TO THE LEFT HIS TRAILER MOVED RIGHT AND GOT ONTO THE SHOULDER WHICH WAS SOFT, THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO REGAIN CONTROL THE TRAILER WENT OFF THE EMBANKMENT DRAGGING THE TRUCK WITH IT, THE TRAILER WENT OVER FIRST AND COME TO REST ON ITS TOP, AND THEN THE TRUCK.    I HAD JUST IMPLEMENTED A SERIES ON ROLL OVERS, WE WILL CONTINUE WITH THAT PROGRAM, HOLDING DRIVER MEETINGS TO GO OVER THE RAMIFICATIONS OF THIS ROLL OVER AND ANY ROLL OVER, WILL START A SERIES ON DRIVER ALERT AND SLEEPING DISORDERS. WE ARE ASSESSING OUR COMPANY POLICY FOR SLEEP APNEA.    PACKAGE FAILURE WAS DUE TO ROLL OVER AND IMPACT WITH SOME TREES, STRIKING THE TREES IS WHAT BREACHED THE TANK. AS FOR PREVENTION, STARTS AT THE DRIVER, FOR BREACHING THE TANKS, I KNOW OF NOTHING IN THE INDUSTRY TODAY THAT WOULD STAND UP TO THE IMPACT OF A TREE OR ANY SOLID OBJECT.

column168: On 3-11-12 the QKCNL-07 with lead unit KCS 4698 on the Laredo subdivision reported being struck from behind by the MCCLR-10 with lead unit KCSM 3015. The last two cars of the train (QKCNL) were struck and derailed. The last two cars on QKCNL were intermodal well cars which contained four hazmat containers (all Class 9 Polymeric Beads, Expandable). All four containers were involved in fire along with two derailed locomotives. This report is for one of the four hazmat containers identified on the train consist as SNLU 138772 (The remaining four containers will be reported on three other individual F5800.1 reports).     Question 11 note--The railroad waybill indicated Schneider (intermodal carrier) as the shipper. The actual origin shipper information was not made availabe to the KCS. Contact Schneider truck line for this information.    Question 13 note--The railroad waybill indicated Schneider (intermodal carrier) as the consignee. The actual final destination is not made available to KCS. Contact Schneider truck line for this information.    Question 26a note--The commodity was contained in 1 ton poly bags. As a result of the fire, the packaging markings were destroyed and un-attainable.    Question 28 note--The hazmat packages were destroyed in the fire. The intermodal container number was reported in question 28.    Question 35 note--The nearest occupied structure to the incident location was 0.75 miles away. No formal evacuation was mandated by the incident commander. However, it is thought that some residents relocated as precaution.

On 3/22/2012 at 0840, an operator at the Charlotte General Products TRANSFLO (transloading) terminal was walking past rail tank car # NTLX 1063 when he noticed a strong product odor. After looking closer at the tank car he discovered liquid dripping from the flange below the primary valve on the rail tank car. Rail tank car # NTLX 1063 contained Propyl Acetate (Hazard Class 3).  A catch pan was immediately placed under the flange to catch additional drips of the hazardous material. It is estimated than less than a gallon of Propyl Acetate was released. The railcar had arrived at the Charlotte GP TRANSFLO terminal on January 20th, 2012 and was not leaking during initial inspection or subsequent inspections. No product had been offloaded from the railcar since its arrival at the TRANSFLO terminal. Inspections by RESCAR and the CSX Hazardous Material division determined that the railcar had a defective Jamesbury bottom outlet valve. The 1 " securement nuts were tightened to slow the release but this did not completely stop the product drip. RESCAR was unable to repair the bottom outlet valve so the shipper arranged for the product to be offloaded into trailers to remove product from railcar and stop the release of product. Shipper (Oxea Corporation) has applied for an FRA movement approval to forward the railcar with product residue to another location for repairs.
column169: All employees were re-trained on visual inspection of all equipment, fittings, and railcars. All employees will continue to inspect railcars upon arrival to the terminal, during their daily walk-around, and before transloading of product is started. If leaks are observed or damage is found on any piece of equipment, fitting, or railcar, it will immediately  be reported to the facility manager for repair.

column62: Broken Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 A.M (CST) ON THURSDAY MARCH 29, 2012, THE NM TRANSFER SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIEDD BY ONE OF OUR DRIVERS OF A SPILL TAKING PLACE AT A DELIVERY LOCATION. THAT LOCATION WAS CAPRON MFG, CAPRON, IL. OUR DRIVER INFORMED US THAT THE IBC HAD RUPTURED. THE IBC WAS LOADED FOUR FEET FROM THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER. IT CONTAINED A CORROSIVE CLEANING COMPOUND(NA 1760). THE CRACK WAS APPROXIMATELY SIX TO EIGHT INCHES LONG AND WAS LOCATED AT THE TOP SIDE OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLE. ALL ALUMINUM SUPPORT BARS ON THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE IBC HAD SNAPPED. (SEE PHOTOS), IT WS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS HAD SPILLED FROM THIS 330 GALLON IBC. THIS IBC WAS SECURED WITH A LOAD BAR, AND HAD SIMILAR PRODUCT LOADED ALONG SIDE OF IT IN BLUE PLASTIC 55 GALLON DRUMS.     THE SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP ON 3/28/12 IN INDIANAPOLIS, IN. IT WAS LINEHAULED IN THAT TRAILER FROM INDIANAPOLIS TO NEENAH., WISCONSIN WHERE THE IBC WAS DOCKED AND THEN RELOADED ON TO ANOTHER TRAILER.    NM TRANSFER HAD SOME RECENT HISTORY OF PACKAGES LEAKING WITH THIS SHIPPER. AS A RESULT, WE BEGAN TAKING PHOTOS OF THESE BULK PACKAGES THROUGH OUT THEIR ARRIVALS WITHIN OUR TRANSPORTATION NETWORK. THIS IBC WAS PHOTOGRAPHED UPON DEPARTURE FROM OUR BREAKBULK TERMINAL IN NEENAH, WI. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY KIND OF DAMAGE TO THE IBC BEFORE IT WAS LOADED OUT. THE DRIVER ALSO VERIFIED WITH ME THAT THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF ANY LEAKAGE OF DAMAGE WHEN HE VIEWED THE IBC ON THE TAIL OF THIS TRAILER AT NEENAH, WI.     THE CUSTOMER WAS NOT ABLE TO REMOVE THE IBC FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER BECAUSE OF THE RISK INVOLVED WITH FURTHER MOVEMENT. N&M TRANSFER NOTIFIED OUR INSURANCE CARRIER TO LOCATE AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY FOR US. THEY CONTACTED S.E.T. ENVIRONMENTAL OUT OF WHEELING, ILLINOIS. S.E.T. RESPONDED WITH A CREW OF FOUR PEOPLE AND THREE VEHICLES WITH EQUIPMENT. THE LEAKING IBC WAS DRAINED AT THE SPILL SITE AND REFILLED IN TO TWO NEW IBC'S. SATURATED CLEAN UP MATERIALS FROM THE SPILL SITE WERE PLACED IN A DRUM FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL. THE ASPHAL GROUND SURFACE WAS CLEANED UP, AS WELL AS THE TRAILER FLOOR. AT LEAST TWO SHIPMENTS LOADED IN FRON AND TO THE SIDE OF THIS IBC WERE SPLATTERED WITH THE CORROSIVE CLEANING COMPOUND. THE SPILL SITE WAS REMOVED OF ALL VEHICLES AT APPRXIMATELY 3:40 PM.
column169: AT THE TIME THIS REPORT WAS BEING WRITTEN, EXPERTS WERE STILL BREING CONSULTED AS TO THE CAUSE OF THIS RUPTURE. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY STACKING OF ANY KIND OF FREIGHT ON THIS IBC. STAKING OF FREIGHT ON TOP OF IBC'S IS STRICTLY PROHIBITED BY OUR COMPANY POLICY. THE INSPECTION MARKS NOTED BY THE SHIPPER AND A DATE STAMPON THE PLASTIC WHITE BOTTLE INDICATES THAT THE TOTE WAS MANUFACTURED IN MARCH OF 2012, HOWEVER, BY APPEARANCE, THE IBC LOOKS MUCH OLDER THAN THAT.    PART 178.707 INDICATES THE FOLLOWING: "COMPOSITE IBC'S INTENDED FOR THE TRANSPORATION OF LIQUIDS MUST BE CAPABLE OF RELEASING A SUFFICIENT AMOUNT OF VAPOR TO PREVENT THE BODY OF THE IBC FROM RUPTURING IF IT IS SUBJECTED TO AN INTERNAL PRESSURE IN EXCESS OF THAT FOR WHICH IT WAS HYDRAULICALLY TESTED. THIS POTENTION CAUSE NEEDS TO BE LOOKED AT FURTHER.     ANOTHER BULK PACKAGE EXPERT WE HAVE MADE CONTACT WITH REGARDING THIS INCIDENT MADE THE FOLLOWING COMMENTS ABOUT COMPOSITE IBC'S."   "WE HAVE TESTED IBC'S BEFORE AND SEE SIMILAR FAILURES DURING THE BOUNCE VIBRATION TEST REQUIRED FOR UN DOT CERTIFICATION FOR HAZARD MATERIAL PACKAGING. MY BEST GUESS IS THAT THE TRAILER RESONATED (BOUNCED UP AND DOWN) AT AROUND 4-5 HZ. IT IS RARE, BUT I HAVE SEEN CERTAIN STRETCHES OF ROAD CAUSE THE TRAILER TO BOUNCE UP AND DOWN AT THAT FREQUENCY. THAT FREQUENCY RANGE CAN CAUSE THE LIQUD TO RESONANT, CAUSING THE SIDEWALLS OF THE IBC TO BOW IN AND OUT. THAT MOVEMENT CAN CAUSE THE METAL FRAMES TO BREAK AND IBC TO RUPTURE"    I RECOMMEND THAT DOT CONSIDER INCREASING THE VIBRATION AND LEAKPROOF STANDARDS FOR MANUFACTURERS OF IBC COMPOSITE PACKAGING. DURING OUR INVESTIGATION WE FOUND THAT THE TRAILER WITH THIS IBC TRAVELED ON ONE VERY ROUGH PORTION OF AN INTERSTATE HIGHWAY (FOR APPROXIMATELY ONE TO TWO MILES), JUST SOUTH OF THE WISCONSIN-ILLINOIS BORDER. VIBRATION AND LEAKPROOF TEST NEED TO HAVE EQUAL OR GREATER LEVELS THAN WHAT IS FOUND ON SOME OF THE ROUGHEST ROADS IN THE US.S. MOTOR CARRIERS CANNOT CONTINUE AFFORD TO CONTINUE TO PAY FOR THE REMEDIATION COST OF BULK OR NON-BULK PACKAGES THAT FAIL DURING HIGHWAY TRANSPORT.

column168: At 10:05 hours on 14 Mar 2012, it was reported that tank car CELX 23285, a loaded Vinyl Acetate tank car, was found leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  The tank car is located in track 500, MP 788.1, Baton Rouge, LA on the New Orleans Subdivision.      US Environmental Services (USES) was contacted by KCS to respond to leaking tank car. Upon investigation, USES found the leak source was from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) steam packing. Responders tightened the packing nut and corrected the release. The responder found the packing nut very loose (not even figure tight). Appeared previous loader/unloaders loosened this packing nut to ease the operation of the BOV and failed to retighten the packing nut. The repair was monitored for 30 minutes to assure a tight closure.   At approximately 11:51 USES notified KCS that the leak was stopped and tank car was secured.    File Note Item 19the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: The driver followed the loading procedures prescribed by the Koch - Enid, OK ammonia plant.  During loading the final few pounds of product the pressure relief valve vented for ten (10) seconds, releasing only vapor and then reset.  The driver observed the tank pressure to be approximately 262 PSI and subsequently asked the plant loading staff at Koch what the plant loading pressure was operating at.  They indicated that the plant was operating 300 PSI. The plant staff did respond to the pressure relief valve venting and checked the environmental conditions, observing them to be safe and observed that the pressure relief valve had reset with no further venting then released the truck.
column169: Transportation Express Management debriefed the driver and discuss actions to prevent future overpressure situations.  The owner-operator replaced the REGO pressure relief valve in the trailer and will place increased attention on monitoring the tank pressure of the trailer during loading.

On March 23, 2012, Veolia ES Technical Solutions (Veolia) was conducting a waste pick-up at Latrobe Specialty Steel (LSS) located in Latrobe, PA.  Veolia arrived at location at approximately 8:45 am to remove seven (7) 275-gallon totes of oil contaminated with Polychlorinated Biphenyls.  The PCB level in the oil was 90 ppm according to the analytical testing previously supplied to Veolia.    A forklift driver from LSS loaded the first tote of seven onto the back of Veolia's truck.  A Veolia employee was using a pallat jack to move tote to the front of the truck.  While the employee was moving the tote, the bottom valve on the tote started to leak.  The tote released approximately 250 gallons of the liquid.  The calculated PCB concentration that was released is 0.19 lbs.    The Veolia employee immediately placed spill pads and booms around the nearby stormwater drain to prevent a release.  The forklift driver from Latrobe Speciality Steel brought bags of oil dry to clean-up and free liquids.  A third party spill clean-up contractor was called in to address the spill and clean-up.    The valve assembly attached to the body appeared to crack and break away from the body while it was being moved into position.  No portion of the valve or valve body came into contact with anything that would have contributed to the failure.
column169: Although the container failure was not a result of any Veolia actions, Veolia conducted a training class with their employees that service the Latrobe, PA area.  The training reviewed the incident, how the container failed, container inspection, and the markings that are required on a tote.

column168: Driver had picked up a drum and placed and secured in his trailer. Upon arrival to his domiciled terminal he backed into his assigned door and when he went to remove his equipment from the inside of the trailer he noticed that a drum had been damaged in transit. Our drivers carry pallet jacks in their trailers to help them load and unload freight. The pallets jacks are secured to the inside of our trailers by chains that are attached to them that clip into the e-track system built into the inner walls of our trailers. During transit the etrack clip became unhooked and as a result the pallet jack became loose and struck the drum resulting in a small hole and contributing to the unintentional release. The spilled material was cleaned with sorbent and placed into a recovery drum along with the damaged drum.
