column168: WHILE STAGED IN THE LOADING AREA, IT WAS DISCOVERED A 55 GALLON DRUM OF LIQUID LEAKING DUE TO BEING PUNCTURED AND DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE DRUM AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND LINED SALVAGE DRUMS. THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS!  RETRAINING IN THE SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN ENTEREING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ESPECIALLY THE LONG BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING THE VARIOUS PACKAGES.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR THE FORKLIFT.

column168: THE CALL CAME IN AT 18:53 SAYING THEY HAD A HAZMAT WITH A WET EDGE.  GOT TO THE SPILL, USED MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP THE PACKAGE, AND GET IT BACK TO PSC FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION.  THE PACKAGE WAS WET A LITTLE BIT IN THE BOTTOM CORNER, AND THE PACKAGE WAS SITTING ON THE GRADING WITH THE ARROWS DOWN, SLOWLY DRIPPING ON THE FLOOR.  THE PACKAGE INSIDE CONSISTED OF A GLASS JAR WITH A LOOSE CAP THAT WAS THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.
WAS CALLED TO A HAZARD SPILL IN THE AIR SORT.  RESPONDED WITH PROPER PPE, SPILL CART AND RESPONSE SHEET IN HAND.  CLEANED UP SPILL.  TOOK PACKAGE BACK TO DMP AREA FOR PROCESSING.

column14: RDI Warehouse at The Point Ind
column168: Dow Agrosciences in Midland, Michigan shipped six tanks full of spent carbon to RDI Construction in South Point, Ohio.  The tanks were not marked as containing hazardous material.  No failure or release of the material occurred.  Upon arrival at RDI, the material inside the tanks was tested and found to have a pH >12.5.  RDI management contacted Calgon Carbon, who contacted their customer Dow Agrosciences.  Calgon created a new manifest for the material, marked the tanks as containing hazardous material, and arranged to have the tanks shipped back to Dow Agrosciences.
column169: Dow Agrosciences must follow their procedure for flushing the tanks before shipping them to RDI Construction.     RDI Construction will continue to monitor the pH of material arriving in tanks from Dow Agrosciences and will not accept hazardous material or allow it to be removed from the tanks.  If hazardous material is discovered, RDI Construction will contact Calgon Carbon to have the material properly labeled and shipped back to Dow Agrosciences.

column168: Truck was headed North bound on US Hwy 101 when it left the road and entered the center divider. The driver attempted to bring the truck back onto the highway causing the vehicle to roll over. The vehicle rolled over onto its left side and then onto its roof ending up on its right side and compromising the tank. The product inside the vehicle became exposed to sparks which ignited the product. The gasoline inside the tank trailer ignighted and engulfed the vehicle in flames. The entire load burned as well as the vehicle and the driver inside the cab. The fire department was not able to get close enough to the vehicle to extinguish the fire and let it burn out. The fire started a small brush fire that was extinguished immediatly and caused damage to US Hwy 101. This was a single vehicle accident and the driver was the only person injured in the crash.
column169: The driver was completely at fault in this incident. The only changes we are looking to make is to possibly at cameras to the trucks to monitor driver behaivior behind the wheel but this type of equipment is very costly. We have held safety meetings and emphasized the importance of driver awareness and rest.

column168: AN EXPERIENCED COMPANY CDL-X DRIVER WAS OPERATING A COMPANY-OWNED VEHICLE TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON A NARROW, TWO-LANE RURAL ROAD DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS AND DRIVING AT A SPEED OF 47 MPH (8 MPH BELOW THE POSTED LIMIT) WHEN HE APPARENTLY BECAME INATTENTIVE WHEREBY CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO DRIFT OFF THE ACROSS THE FOG LINE TO A GRASS-COVERED RIGHT-OF-WAY. AS THE DRIVER BEGUN A CONTERMEASURE TO RECOVVER, THE VEHICLE REAR AXLES ENCOUNTERED A CULVERT AREA LATERALLY CHANGING MOMENTUM CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO ROTATE CLOCKWISE COMING TO REST ON IT DRIVER SIDE.    DRIVER UNHOOKED HIS SEAT BELT, SHUT OFF THE ENGINE, EXITED THE CAB, AND SHUT OFF THE BATTERY SWITCH. THE COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN WAS PUT INTO EFFECT WITH 911, CHEMTREC AND THE DRIVERS HOME TERMINAL CALLED. THE DRIVER REMOVED DIVISION 1.4 EXPLOSIVE MATERIALS FROM THE PASSENGER SIDE IME-22 CONTAINER. THE CARRIER'S COMPANY IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED A QUALIFIED SPILL CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE. THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED. THE DRIVER'S HOME TERMIANL DISPATCHED COMPANY PERSONNEL AND A COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE TO ASSIST FIRST RESPONDERS IN CRASH RECOVERY. THE CRASH VEHICLE WAS UP-RIGHTED BY A WRECKER, AND COMPANY PERSONNEL REMOVED THE DIVISION 1.1 EXPLOSIVES ROM THE DRIVER SIDE IME-22 CONTAINER.     THE INCIDENT INVOLVED SPILLS OF 700-LBS OF AMMONIOUM NITRATE, 10 GALLONS OF COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID AND 20 GALLONS OF ACETIC ACID OCCURRED. NO INJURIES OF FATALITIES OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT. NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED IN THE INCIDNET. THE CRASH VEHICLE WAS TOWED FROM THE CRASH SCENE. THE PUBLIC HIGHWAY SOUTHBOUND WAS CLOSED FOR 11.5 HOURS AND 2 RESIDENCES WERE INITIALLY EVACUATED.
column169: AFTER CONSIDERABLE REVIEW OF THE FACTS AND CONCLUSIONS OF THIS INCIDENT.    1. THE AUSTIN POWDER MANAGEMENT TEAM WILL SCHEDULE,ORGANIZE AND CONDUCT A SPECIAL SAFETY MEETING WITH THE LOCATION HAZMAT DRIVERS. THE SAFETY MEETING WILL INVOLVE GROUP TRAVEL TO THE INCIDENT AREA TO FOLLOW THE RURAL ROAD PART OF ROUTE 61 UP TO AND INCLUDING THE CRASH SCENE AREA FOLLOWED BY A DISCUSSION ON THE DANGERS AND RISKS ASSOCIATED WITH RURAL, INATTENTIVE DRIVING. THE AGENDA AND ATTENDANCE OF THIS MEETING WILL BE DOCUMENTED.    2. THE AUSTIN POWDER TRAINING DEPARTMENT WILL PROVIDE A REFRESHER DRIVING SAFTY PROGRAM TO BE REQUIRED OF ALL COMPANY HAZMAT DRIVERS ADDRESSING INATTENTIVE, RURAL DRIVING AND ROLLOVERS AND REINFORCED SMITH SYSTEM SAFE DRIVING PRINCIPLES.    3. ONCE CONSTRUCTION OF THE (NEW) ROUTE 61 IS COMPLETD THIS YEAR, AUSTIN HAZMAT VEHICLES WILL BE ROUTED ON IT FOR THEIR TRIPS THROUGH THIS AREA OF KENTUCKY, THEREBY AVOIDING THE OLD HIGHWAY.

column168: Local Yard Master reported vapor emitting from top of loaded tank car TILX 110370.  Inspection of car revealed the frangible disk within the safety vent assembly had ruptured.  Failed disk was removed and replaced with a Zook #165 disk.  Cause of disk failure was due to over pressurization resulting from hydraulic surge of product while car was in movement. Upon replacement of the disk, car was released to continue onto destination without further incident.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column43: LEAD ACID BATTERIES, NEW AND JUNKS
column168: THE INCIDENT TOOK PLACE AT THE INTERSECTION OF WEST BRADLEY AND NORTH 76 STREET IN MILWAUKEE, WI. ONE OF EAST PENN'S DRIVERS WAS TRAVELING SOUHTH ON NORTH 76 STREET APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION OF WEST BRADLEY AND NORTH 76 STREET WHEN HE HEARD TIRES SCREECHING AND INTSTANTLY FELT AN IMPACT TO THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE TRACTOR (STEERING AXLE/TIRE, DRIVER DOOR AND FUEL TANK). THE DRIVER TRIED TO STEER HIS TRACTOR BUT HE WAS UNABLE TO STEER BECAUSE THE DRIVER'S SIDE STEERING TIRE WAS FOLDED UNDER THE TRACTOR DUE TO THE IMPACT. AFTER THE INITIAL IMPACT, THE DRIVER WAS COASTING INTO THE OPPOSITE LANE OF TRAVEL ON NORTH 76 STREET (HEADING SOUTH IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE). AS THE DRIVER WAS COASTING TO A STOP HIS TRACTOR IMPACTED A VEHICLE (FLATBED STAKE BODY) TRAVELING NORTH ON NORTH 76 STREET CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO FLIP OVER ON ITS SIDE.     ACCORDING TO STATEMENTS AT THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT, IT APPEARS THAT TWO AUTOMOBILES HAD A COLLISION FIRST CAUSING ONE OR BOTH OF THE VEHICLES TO IMPACT THE EAST PENN TRACTOR ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE. THIS SET FORTH THE ABOVE CHAIN REACTION OF EVENTS.    THE EAST PENN DRIVER WAS HAULING BOTH NEW AND JUNK BATTERIES, WET FILLED WITH ACID AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. FROM THE IMPACT, THE BATTERIES SHIFTED. THE TOTAL APPROXIMATE WEIGHT OF THE LOAD AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT WAS 30,500- 31,500 LBS. APPROXIMATE 20 GALLONS OF ACID WAS LOST FROM CRACKED OR DAMAGED BATTERIES DUE TO THE SHIFT. ONLY 120 BATTERIES (APPROXIMATELY 400 LBS) WERE DAMAGED PRODUCT.     THE MILWAUKEE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE FOR CONTAINMET OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS LEAK. THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT TO ANY STORM DRAINS, WATER WAYS, OR SOIL. IT WAS DETERMINED TO OFF LOAD ALL THE NON-LEAKING BATTERIES AND RELOAD THEM ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER. THE DAMAGED BATTERIES HAD THE ACID DRAINED INTO AN OVER PACK DRUM. THE DRAINED BATTERIES WERE PLACED ON ACID ABSORBENT PADS. THE ACID THAT LEAKED IN THE TRAILER WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH. BOTH THE DAMAGED TRAILER AND THE EXTRA RE-LOADED TRAILER WERE TRANSPORTED TO A NEAR BY TOWING SERVICE'S PARKING LOT.     IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CLEAN UP EFFORTS BY THE MILWAUKEE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS SUFFICIENT FOR CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILL. EAST PENN MFG HIRED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY TO CONTINUE EFFORTS IN THE CLEAN UP AND RE-PACKAGING OF THE BATTERIES FOR PROPER SHIPPING AND PROPER DISPOSAL OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE THAT WAS GENERATED. ALL OF THE BATTERIES WERE EVENTUALLY SENT BACK TO EAST PENN MFG, OELWEIN, IA FOR DETERMINATION OF GOOD PRODUCT AND SCRAP. THE SCRAP BATTERIES WILL BE PROCESSED AT A LOCAL SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER.

column168: At approximately 6:45 A.M. KCS Hazmat, contacts Hulcher services to request a crew respond to a possible leaking tank car at the KCS Knoche Yard, in Kansas City, MO. Car number NATX37283 was reported to have Petroleum Crude oil leaking from under the protective dome.  Robert Waln, SDM Hulcher Services, is contacted to respond to the incident. Robert Waln, SDM Hulcher Services Inc. arrives on site and Waln proceed to the car shop, KCS Car shop foreman, to arrange for track protection.     KCS locked and flags on Track 32 + 31.  The Hulcher crew proceeded to start an assessment of the tank car. An assessment of the car is completed.      It was discovered by the Hulcher crew that there was product leaking from between the 4 bolt flange and the ball valve on the liquid line of the car.  The liquid line valve assembly was tightened.  All valves were verified closed and plugs were installed.  The protective dome was closed and secured with seal #587792.  The jacket of the car was wiped with absorbent pads to reduce the amount of residue. The Hulcher crew is off the clock for this incident at this time.    File Note Item 19 the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THEY PROVIDED A MSDS THAT SHOWED TWO PRODUCTS THAT HAD FLASH POINTS OF 100 DEGREES FARENHEIT, AND THE OTHER HAD 141 DEGREES FARENHEIT. I THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TO SEE IF THEY HAD ANY FURTHER INFORMATION, BUT THEY DID NOT. I THEN CONTACTED DAVE SCHAUFLER OF THE MKC/FAA OFFICE AT 10:30 (CDT) ON 3-30-2012 TO ADVISE OF THIS INCIDENT. HE WAS GOING TO ASSIGN FOLLOW-UP TO ONE OF HIS REPORTS. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING THEIR INVESTIGATION.

KEN HOLMAN OF THE MEM/FAA OFFICE WAS CONTACTED BY VOICEMAIL AT 8:15 ON TUESDAY MARCH 27, 2012 TO INFORM OF THE INCIDENT. column168: DURING THE LOADING PROCESS (ENTERING THE TRAILER FROM OFF THE CHUTE) THE PACKAGE WAS TURNED SIDEWAYS AND LEAKED FROM THE INSUFFICIENT CLOSURES OF THE CONTAINERS INSIDE. THIS CAUSED LEAKAGE ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. ONCE THE MATERIAL HAD BEEN IDENTIFIED AND CLEANED I DETEMINED THAT IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN IN AN APPROPRIATELY LABELED CONTAINER AND SHOULD HAVE BEEN SHIPPED AS A HAZMAT FOLLOWING APPRPRIATE SHIPPING PROCEDURES. DUE TO THE FACT THAT NONE OF THE CONTAINERS COULD BE CLOSED COMPLETELY TO PREVENT LEAKAGE, I DETERMINED IT WOULD BE BEST TO PROCESS THROUGH THE DMP RATHER THAN CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR PICK UP.

column168: THE PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK.  IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, A VEHICLE BACKED THROUGH THE CONED AREA THAT THE DRIVER HAD BLOCKED OFF AND STRUCK THE DELIVERY FITTING THAT WAS CONNECTED TO THE TANK. THIS CAUSED THE DELIVERY FITTING TO BREAK AND 20 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED.  SET ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.

THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTIMG TO DELIVER DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK.  IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, HE OPENED THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE TRAILER PRIOR TO CONNECTING THE HOSE TO THE STORAGE TANK.  AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.  UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION.  NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

THE TRUCK WAS DRIVEN TO THE NEXT PICKUP LOCATION (NEXUS - 6220 W. 73RD ST. / BEDFORD PARK, IL) AND ANOTHER DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER.  THE LME DRIVER INSPECTED THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THE FOUR DRUMS WERE LYING ON THEIR SIDES IN THE TRAILER.                                                                               ACTIONS TAKEN:  THE LME DRIVER CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR AND THEN CALLED CHEMTREC AND THE CARRIER (LAKEVILLE MOTOR EXPRESS) TO REPORT THE RELEASE.  THE LME DRIVER ALSO NOTIFIED THE BUSINESS (NEXUS) OF THE RELEASE.  NEXUS PERSONNEL NOTIFIED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  LME PERSONNEL CALLED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC., AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY FOR THE CARRIER.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT  DISPATCHED A LOCAL QUALIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY TO PERFORM CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES.  THE CLEAN-UP CREW MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AND UPRIGHTED THE DRUMS.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A PLASTIC SALVAGE DRUM.  THE CREW THEN USED CLAY ABSORBENTS TO REMOVE THE RELEASED PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND FROM THE DRIVEWAY UNDER THE TRAILER.  THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS WERE COLLECTED AND STAGED FOR  DISPOSAL.  A STORM DRAIN WAS IMPACTED BY THE RELEASED PRODUCT.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE METROPOLITAN WATER RECLAMATION DISTRICT WAS CALLED TO THE SITE AND INSTRUCTED THE CREW TO PLACE ONE, 50-LB BAG OF SODIUM BICARBONATE INTO THE STORM DRAIN TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  ALL WASTE FROM THE CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES HAS BEEN SENT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  PACKAGE FAILURE:  THE BUNG PLUG ON TOP OF THE DRUM WAS DISLODGED WHEN THE OTHER TREE DRUMS FELL ON TOP OF THE FOURTH DRUM.                           DURATION OF FAILURE:  THE RELEASE IS ESTIMATED AT 40 GALLONS, BASED ON THE REMAINING LIQUID IN THE LEAKING DRUM.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: Driver of transport vehicle noticed smoke coming from right side of trailer. Stopped to investigate.  Discovered right front tire had blown and wheel/rim had been running on roadway.  Shortly afterwards the tire caught fire. Driver used portable fire extinguisher to put out fire and call 911 for assistance.  Tire re-ignited and spread to multiple tires.  Transport vehicle has only four tires, one per wheel position.  The trailer is a fiberglass composite tank.  The fire burned off the external valve and piping which is also a plastic or PVC type material.  The internal valve was heated to the extent that the viton gasketing material melted and failed, allowing the product contained to leak from the container.  Fire Department extinguished the fire and as the vessel cooled the leak decreased.  Hepaco Environmental was contracted by the carrier to respond.  Leaking materials were diked.  Materials remaining in the transport vehicle were transferred to another transport and taken back to shipper for analysis. Tare weights compared indicate a loss of 940 gallons of bleach.  The site location will be restored as per SC recommendations in conjunction with Hepaco.  There are 25 tons of impacted soils that will be disposed of.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND HWY 52 AT APPROXIMATELY 58 TO 60 MPH, NOTICED TWO RACCOONS ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE ROAD; TOOK CRUISE OFF VEHICLE AND LOOKED INTO HIS MIRROR TO CHANGE LANES.  HE LOOKED INTO THE LEFT MIRROR AGAIN AND HIS FRONT DRIVE TIRE WENT INTO THE SOFT GRAVEL LOCATED ON THE LEFT SIDE SHOULDER AND WENT OFF THE ROAD, HE WAS LOADED WITH APPROX. 8,800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  AS THE TANKER ENTERED THE MEDIAN THIS CAUSED THE TANKER TO OVERTURN AND COME TO A FINAL REST ON IT'S RIGHT SIDE IN THE MEDIAN FACING SOUTH.  WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS RESPONDED TO THE CRASH SITE, WHO WERE HIRED BY KWIK TRIP, TO ASSIST IN CONTAINING AND CLEAN UP OF SPILL.  WCEC STATED, DUE TO THE RESULT OF THE ROLLOVER, A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF GASOLINE LEAKED FROM ONE OF THE DOME COVERS ON THE TRAILER.  WCEC USED ABSORBENT PADS UNDERNEATH THE COVER TO COLLECT MOST OF THE PRODUCT, AND PLACE A CONTAINMENT POOL UNDERNEATH THE DOME COVER AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE IN THE EVENT GASOLINE SHOULD START TO LEAK AGAIN.  THREE DRUMS OF SOIL WERE FILLED WITH THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND ABSORBENT PADS, AND PID READINGS WERE TAKEN TO SPOT CHECK THE SURROUNDING AREA FOR FURTHER CONTAMINATION AND NO DETECTION ABOVE AMBIENT READINGS WAS NOTED.

THE MARCH 20, 2012 INCIDENT ON INTERSTATE 294 SOUTHBOUND AT MILE MARKER 12.9 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:40 P.M. INVOLVED VEHICLE OR UNIT 1, A FORD ECONOLINE DRIVEN BY THOMAS J. STEWART, AND VEHICLE OR UNIT 2, A MACK TRACTOR DRIVEN BY TIMOTHY J. PULLI, HAULING A 5,000 GALLON TANKER OWNED BYT PFA SYSTEMS, INC., AND THEN LEASED BY PFA TO PULLI EXPRESS, INC. THE TANKER CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  JUST PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT, UNIT 1 WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON I-294. IN THIS AREA OF THE TOLL ROAD, THE TOLL ROAD IS DIVIDED BY RAISED CONCRETE BARRIERS IN THE MEDIAN STRIP. HOWEVER, NEAR THE INCIDENT LOCATION, THERE IS AN OPENING IN THE CENTER MEDIAN, AND THE DRIVER OF UNIT 1, THOMAS J. STEWART, MADE AN ILLEGAL U-TURN AND THEN ENTERED THE SOUTHBOUND LANES OF I-294 DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF UNIT 2. THE SOUTHBOUND I-294 TRACTOR/TANKER, UNIT 2, TOOK EVASIVE ACTION TO AVOID UNIT 1, AND THE TRACTOR/TANKER ROLLED OVER ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF UNIT 2. THE TANKER ALSO RELEASED A SMALL AMOUNT OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID, WHICH RELEASE WAS RESPONDED TO BY THE ALSIP FIRE DEPARTMENT PFA'S CONTRACTOR HAZCHEM, AND OTHERS.

column168: AN ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT THE JUNCTION OF ROUTE 4 AND ROUTE 22 JUST OUTSIDE OF FORT ANNE, NY. THE WEATHER AT THE TIME WAS HEAVY RAIN WITH TEMPERATURE HOVERING AROUND FREEZING. A TRACTOR TRAILER TYPE UNIT LOADED WITH 7500 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL WAS TRAVELING NORTH IN A LINE OF TRAFFIC AT APPROXIMATELY 30 TO 40MPH APPROACHING AN INTERSECTION WITH A SIGNAL. THE LIGHT WAS CHANGING FROM GREEN TO RED AND TRAFFIC WAS SLOWING.  THE DRIVER APPLIED THE BRAKES THEN PROCEEDED TO DOWNSHIFT AND STOP FOR THE LIGHT. THE ACTUAL CAUSE COULD NOT BE DETERMINED EITHER BY THE DRIVER OR THE RESPONDING OFFICER, BUT THE TRAILER BRAKES FAILED TO RELEASE. UNDER NORMAL CONDITIONS THE VEHICLE WOULD HAVE SLOWED TO A STOP, BUT UNDER WET AND ICY CONDITIONS THE TRAILER SLID ONTO THE SHOULDER AND DOWN THE SLOPED EMBANKMENT RESULTING IN A ROLL OVER. ALTHOUGH THE ROAD WAS SLIPPERY AT THE TIME, WE FEEL THE REAL CAUSE WAS THE BRAKES ON THE TRAILER FAILING TO RELEASE. THE TRUCK WAS AT POINT COMPLETELY OFF THE ROAD AND LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE AIR SPACE BETWEEN COMPARTMENT #3 AND #4. THE AIR SPACE IS DESIGNED TO STOP A LEAKING BULKHEAD FROM CONTAMINATING THE PRODUCT IN THE NEXT COMPARTMENT.  UNFORTUNATELY, THIS AIR SPACE HAS A DRAIN HOLE ON THE BOTTOM ALLOWING PRODUCT TO DRAIN OUT. THE DRIVER TRIED TO PLUG THOSE HOLES, BUT THE FIRE RESPONDERS WOULDN'T ALLOW ANYONE NEAR THE LEAKING PRODUCT. WHEN THE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDERS ARRIVED THEY WERE ABLE TO DRIVE WOODEN PLUGS INTO THE DRAIN THUS CONTAINING THE REST OF THE PRODUCT.
column169: THE FIREMEN ARE TRAINED AS TO WHEN RESPONDING TO AN ACCIDENT TO KEEP EVERYONE AWAY, ESPECIALLY IF THE LOAD IS HAZARDOUS. THE ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE WOULD HAVE BEEN RELATIVELY LIGHT HAD THE FIRE RESPONDERS ATTEMPTED TO ALLOW THE DRIVER TO PLUG THE DRAIN HOLES. THE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO RELATIVELY QUICKLY AND EASILY STOP THE FLOW. I UNDERSTAND THEIR FIRST CONCERN IS SAFETY, BUT IN MANY CASES THE DRIVERS INPUT IS MORE VALUABLE.    TO MY KNOWLEDGE, THIS AIRSPACE IS DESIGNED TO BE OPEN TO THE ATMOSPHERE. WOULD IT BE POSSIBLE TO PLUG THOSOE DRAIN HOLES DURING TRANSPORTATION? ALTHOUGH THE BAFFLES AND THE BULKHEAD RUPTURED, THE MAIN PARTS OF THE TANK REMAINED INTACT. THE BARREL, VENTS AND DOME COVERS HELD. IF THE AIR SPACE WAS SEALED THERE WOULD HAVE BEEN LITTLE OR NO SPILLAGE.

column168: On March 16, 2012, at approximately 0300 hours a Vitran tractor trailer stuck a section of guardrail and a section of concrete sign support.  The impact of the accident caused the tractor and trailer to catch fire.  The fire spread throughout the trailer and caused the drums of UN1866 to burst.  The material releases approximately 3520 pounds.  The fire department extinguished the fire and the UN1866 impacted water migrated into a drainage ditch.  The fire department contained the release with absorbent boom.  Best personnel arrived onsite and applied granular absorbents to solidify the puddles of impacted water. The debris was stock piled next to the concrete support, covered with poly, and surrounded with absorbent boom.  On April 2, 2012, Best returned to collect the stock pile and excavate the impacted soil.  An area of 30'x40'x4" was removed and back filled to its original condition.  Confirmation samples were taken and the analytical data showed that the detection levels were below VOC's and SVOC levels.  The THP-ERO detection levels were 25.8 mg/kg, Best requests closure for this site on behalf of Vitran Express.

column168: Our truck and trailer was struck by a passenger car causing our driver to lose control of the truck. As the fire spread, the entire tank was compromised resulting in the remainder of the fuel igniting.  A passing motorist reported the accident to Austin PD and Officers and the Fire Department were dispatched to the scene.  The escaping fuel was allowed to burn which resulted in less environmetal damage.  The area affected by the release was cleaned up by TAS Environmental.Several yards of contaminated dirt was removed and when the area was declared clean by TCEQ, fresh dirt was hauled in and spread over the area that had been affected.  After this was completed, grass seen was spread over the area.

The drive said he was delivering a 1,000 gallon Anhydrous Ammonia tank to a farmer's field behind a 3/4 ton pickup at about 20mph as he was making a slight tun to the left he felt a slam or jerk to the truck.  He looked in the rear view mirror and saw the tank had turned over, at that time he felt the brakes must have locked up on the truck.  When he came to a stop he checked the condition of the tank it was on it's side and the front liquid valve handle had broken off and there was a small Anhydrous leaking out. The tank was in the roadway, the opposite lane was open to traffic so he called 911 to have the roadway closed for safety and to notify the local fire department for assistance in handling the release. When the fire department arrived they contacted a local excavating company who came to the site with a large pay loader the tank was picked up and set in a nearby field.  At this time an empty Anhydrous tank was brought to the site and we began transferring the Anhydrous Ammonia into the empty tank. The duration of the release lasted about 45 minutes.

column168: None reportable spill from tank 3 Crown Bay Marina 8169 Subbase St.Thomas  United  States Virgin Islands 00802 tank farm inside their facility 780 gallons of diesel fuel March 27,20l2 around 09:40am, our contract driver Ted Hedrington with 3 years delivering fuel for Chevron Caribbean Inc, was attempting to deliver to Crown Bay Marina 84168 Subbase St. Thomas USVI 00802. The delivery was to a 50,000 gallon above ground storage tank using his PTO. The contract driver was on his first delivery of the day when the incident occurred. The driver had 6,000 gallons of diesel in his truck tank for Crown Bay Marina. The driver immediately stop the flow of product when  he heard product splashing and call for help from the marina staff via VHF (radio he also contacted CVX on the same radio. There were no injuries fatalities, fire, damage to equipment or package failure including holes, cracks etc., from this spill event. None of the spilled product reached navigable waters.    Our contract driver was on the last 2,000 compartment when the Incident occurred and stops the pump immediately.  CVX supported the Crown Bay Marina operators and staff with pumping the spill fuel form the secondary containment dike area of the facility to the correct storage tank. Then continued with the discharge to the correct storage tank without incident and returned to CVX terminal for debriefing.    At this site Chevron Caribbean was no operational control of the tank gauging, pipeline alignment or storage tank alignment all under the control of CBM. The information gathered during the investigation of the spill showed the Crown Bay Marina Operator miss-understood the instruction giving to him from CM Facilities Manager. He was instructed to receive in tank  one and discharge from tank two. The operator set everything in reverse he received in tank two (which did not have enough space to take all of the fuel) and discharge from thank one.    Also 760 gallons of the 780 gallons of the diesel fuel was recovered from the secondary containment and the estimate 20 gallons was in the cleanup absorbent materials (which were disposed by) Virgin Islands Waste Management.    Crown Bay Marina took full responsibility for the incident and made all of the notifications to. NRC (report #1006986 contact Rawls), local fire department, USCG local USVI Department of Planning and Natural Resources.
